The DES MCPs were pre-conditioned by extracting signal charge to a level of 0.1C/cm2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$0.1~\mbox{C}/\mbox{cm}^{2}$\end{document} in a bake-and-scrub facility at GSFC. A UV source and a Ni63 source were used for the burn-in process with the bulk of the charge being extracted by UV illumination. Periodically the UV source was interrupted, leaving only the Ni63 source to excite the MCPs at lower rates and allowing a measurement of the electron pulse height distributions. The MCP stack gain was tracked throughout, measured as the ratio of the first and zeroth integral moments of the pulse height distribution, and width, estimated as the ratio of the FWHM of the pulse height distributions divided by the gain. There was no separate bake-out during the conditioning process.

A MCP life test, extracting nearly 20C/cm2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
