DxS low voltage power converter—power interfaces

Here we describe the basic DxS function, with special emphasis on the Fast Survey mode of operation when MMS is in the scientific region of interest. Each DxS is a pair of particle spectrometers designed to measure differential directional flux in a selected energy range and from selected directions. Particles enter the sensor head aperture through a double grid and pass through deflector plates to the ESA; together, these components constitute the optics of the spectrometer. The deflector plate potential selects the azimuth angle look direction. The top hat ESA analyzer selects plasma particles that fall within its energy resolution, dE/E\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$dE/E$\end{document}, centered at an energy equal to the product of the applied voltage and the ESA Analyzer Constant (kϵ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$k_{\epsilon }$\end{document}). Particles of higher energy fly wide and hit the outer ESA wall and those of lower energy are driven into the inner ESA wall. Particles that pass through the ESA without impacting a wall are detected and counted.

For every 16-element discrete anode array the same anode numbering convention (0–15) is used. Since the two sensors in a DxS are assembled back-to-back, the anode arrays are flipped with respect to one another in the spacecraft frame of reference. For example, a plasma particle moving toward the spacecraft from +Z\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$+\mbox{Z}$\end{document} (in the spacecraft reference frame its vector velocity points in the −Z\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$-\mbox{Z}$\end{document} direction) would detected by DxS Sensor 0 in anode 0, but be detected in Sensor 1 in anode 15. Therefore an FPI convention is adopted such that ‘anodes’ and ‘pixels’ are defined separately. The anode array is defined in the frame of reference of the detector system, while the pixel array is defined in the frame of reference of the DxS which, when mounted on the spacecraft, is identical to the spacecraft frame, to within an azimuth phase shift. In the example above, the particle would be detected in pixel 0 in either Sensor 0 or Sensor 1.

