				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$E/q$\end{document} range near 500 V (Fig. 36c). This effect will have the important and unfortunate impact that the saturation performance of the MCP will be a function of E/q\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$E/q$\end{document}, becoming most severe for DIS near 500 eV/q. This is because MCP detectors saturate on the basis of event rate per unit area. Since the beam spot is smallest near 500 eV this will be the energy/charge at which the onset of event rate saturation will occur at the lowest event rates. If unaccounted for, this effect will produce incorrect distribution function dependence on energy at large event rates. Fig. 36
